ers between Marcus and Fronto will rightfully be reconsidered as key documents in the study of the history of sexuality and classics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLove-letterszRome. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ahistory, historical, academic, scholarly, famous person, classics, classical, manuscript, discovery, antiquity, letters, correspondence, romance, romantic, orator, roman, rome, ancient, italy, 19th century, 1800s, passion, fronto, public eye, culture, cultural, pupil, teacher, relationships, sexuality, sexual, homosexual, homosexuality, gay, lgbtqia, homoerotic.1 aFronto, Marcus Cornelius, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRichlin, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022671300740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226713021423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226713021/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles